    "calculator": false,
    "isLatex": false,
    "format": "text",
    "question": "In a marine food web, anchovies eat phytoplankton, tuna eat anchovies, and dolphins eat tuna. If a pollutant causes a 70% decline in phytoplankton, which of the following is the most likely cascade effect?",
    "choices": [
      "A) Tuna populations increase because they no longer compete with anchovies for phytoplankton.",
      "B) Dolphin populations increase as tuna become easier to catch due to reduced numbers.",
      "C) Anchovy populations decline, followed by declines in tuna and then dolphin populations.",
      "D) Dolphin populations are unaffected because they are apex predators with no natural predators."
    ],
    "answer": 2,
    "explanation": "A trophic cascade occurs when a disturbance at one level propagates through the food web. A 70% decline in phytoplankton reduces food available to anchovies, causing their decline, which in turn reduces food for tuna, then dolphins. Option A is incorrect - tuna do not eat phytoplankton, so there is no competition between tuna and anchovies for phytoplankton. Option B misunderstands that declining prey populations make predators easier to catch (fewer prey means less food, not easier hunting). Option D is a common misconception; apex predators are still dependent on lower trophic levels through the food chain."
