    "format": "text",
    "question": "According to the theory of island biogeography, which of the following islands would be expected to have the highest species richness at equilibrium?",
    "choices": [
      "A) A large island located far from the mainland",
      "B) A small island located close to the mainland",
      "C) A large island located close to the mainland",
      "D) A small island located far from the mainland"
    ],
    "answer": 2,
    "explanation": "Island biogeography theory states that species richness is determined by two factors: immigration rate and extinction rate. Large islands support more species because larger area reduces extinction (more habitat and resources). Islands close to the mainland have higher immigration rates because colonizers don't travel as far. Therefore, a large island close to the mainland maximizes immigration and minimizes extinction, producing the highest species richness. Options A and B each get one factor right but not both. Option D gets both factors wrong."
