    "explanation": "The defining characteristic of a keystone species is that its ecological role and impact on biodiversity are disproportionately large relative to its biomass or abundance. Sea otters control sea urchin populations, which in turn allows kelp forests to persist - supporting dozens of other species. This outsized effect at low biomass is what makes them a keystone species. Choice A is wrong because keystone species are specifically NOT defined by high abundance; that describes a dominant species. This is one of the most common student misconceptions. Choice C is wrong because not all apex predators are keystone species - a keystone species is specifically identified by disproportionate community impact, not simply trophic position. Choice D incorrectly conflates keystone species with ecosystem engineers (like beavers), which alter the physical environment; sea otters regulate community structure through predation, not physical habitat modification."
