    "answer": 0,
    "explanation": "Choice A is correct. The rebound effect (also a manifestation of Jevons paradox at the consumer level) occurs when increased efficiency lowers the effective cost of use, leading consumers to consume more of the service - in this case, driving more miles because each mile costs less in fuel. This is a well-documented phenomenon in transportation economics and is a key AP Environmental Science concept. It illustrates that technological efficiency alone cannot guarantee reduced resource consumption without policies that address total demand. Choice B describes a real regulatory issue (the light truck loophole) but misidentifies it as 'the rebound effect' - this is a classic student misconception. The light truck loophole is a separate problem, not the rebound effect. Choice C confuses the rebound effect with manufacturing-phase life cycle impacts, which, while real, do not primarily explain the shortfall in projected gasoline savings post-CAFE. Choice D describes a market adoption barrier, which is a different phenomenon - fleet efficiency has generally tracked toward CAFE targets over time, making this explanation less accurate than the rebound effect."
