    "answer": 1,
    "explanation": "Choice B is correct. This describes the rebound effect (also related to the Jevons Paradox): when technology makes resource use more efficient, the effective cost of using that resource per unit of activity drops, which often induces greater consumption of that activity. In the case of fuel efficiency, cheaper per-mile driving costs encourage people to drive more, commute farther, or purchase larger vehicles, which reduces the net environmental benefit of the efficiency gain. This is a critical concept in environmental policy analysis. Choice A is incorrect - higher-octane gasoline does not inherently release more CO2 per gallon; CO2 emissions are primarily determined by carbon content and volume burned, not octane rating. Choice C contains a partial truth (fleet turnover is slow) but overstates the case - improvements in new vehicle efficiency do reduce aggregate emissions over time as older vehicles retire, and 'centuries' is a gross exaggeration. Choice D is a distractor combining two misconceptions: lighter vehicles do not always have higher lifecycle footprints, and the claim that efficient vehicles always have higher total carbon footprints than conventional ones is not supported by lifecycle analysis evidence."
