    "answer": 0,
    "explanation": "The correct answer synthesizes two distinct concepts. First, limestone (calcium carbonate, CaCO₃) acts as a natural buffer - it reacts with incoming acids to neutralize them, maintaining a higher pH in Lake B. Granite lacks this buffering capacity, leaving Lake A vulnerable to acidification from the same acid deposition. Second, coal combustion releases SO₂, which oxidizes in the atmosphere to form sulfuric acid (H₂SO₄), a primary component of acid rain. Scrubbers (flue-gas desulfurization systems) chemically react with SO₂ before it exits the smokestack, preventing it from entering the atmosphere. Option B is wrong on two counts: granite does not actively produce acid compounds, and scrubbers target SO₂, not NO₂; also NOₓ-derived nitric acid, while a contributor, is not the dominant component addressed by industrial scrubbers. Option C misrepresents the buffering mechanism - limestone in bedrock buffers water chemistry, it does not absorb atmospheric SO₂ directly - and scrubbers do not release CaCO₃ into watersheds. Option D incorrectly attributes the pH difference to precipitation volume rather than buffering chemistry, and while particulate matter can act as condensation nuclei, this is not the primary mechanism by which scrubbers reduce acid rain."
