    "explanation": "Region A, with consistently high temperatures (~27°C year-round) and very high precipitation (~2,500 mm/year), matches the defining characteristics of a tropical rainforest — high, stable temperatures with no cold season and abundant rainfall. Region B, with pronounced seasonal temperature swings (4°C to 22°C) and the same high precipitation, most closely matches a temperate deciduous forest, where seasonal cold drives leaf-drop adaptations. Option A reverses the correct assignment. Option C is incorrect because boreal forest (taiga) is characterized by very cold winters, short summers, and relatively low precipitation (~300–850 mm/year) — not the moderate-to-warm seasonal temperatures and high precipitation of Region B. Option D is incorrect because a savanna is defined by distinct wet and dry seasons with moderate precipitation (~500–1,500 mm/year), not by 2,500 mm of annual rainfall, and a temperate rainforest, while possible in Region B, requires a specific coastal context not described here, making temperate deciduous forest the stronger match."
