    "question": "A volcanic eruption deposits thick lava over a landscape, destroying all soil and organisms and leaving only bare rock. Over time, living organisms begin to recolonize the area. Which of the following correctly identifies the type of ecological succession occurring and provides the best justification?",
    "choices": [
      "A) Primary succession, because there is no remnant soil or biological community from which recovery can begin.",
      "B) Secondary succession, because the area was once part of a functioning ecosystem before the eruption.",
      "C) Secondary succession, because the disturbance was severe enough to reset the ecosystem to an earlier successional stage.",
      "D) Primary succession, because the eruption introduced new minerals to the surface, providing nutrients for pioneer species."
    ],
    "answer": 0,
    "explanation": "The correct answer is A. Primary succession occurs when an area lacks soil and has no remnant biological community, requiring colonization to begin essentially from scratch. A lava flow that destroys all soil and organisms creates exactly these conditions — bare rock with no seed bank, organic matter, or surviving organisms. The absence of soil is the defining criterion distinguishing primary from secondary succession. Choice B is incorrect because the prior existence of an ecosystem does not determine succession type; what matters is whether soil and a biological legacy remain after the disturbance, not what existed before. Choice C is incorrect because severity of disturbance alone does not define secondary succession — secondary succession is specifically defined by the presence of remnant soil and biological material, not simply by how intense the disturbance was. Choice D is incorrect because while lava does introduce minerals, this is not the defining reason the succession is primary; the correct basis is the complete absence of soil and prior biological community, not mineral input."
