    "explanation": "Option A is correct. When a predator's removal triggers cascading effects downward through trophic levels — reducing prey control and thereby altering lower trophic levels — this is a top-down trophic cascade. Sea otters control sea urchin populations; without otters, urchins overgraze kelp, collapsing a foundational habitat. Sea otters are a classic textbook example of a keystone species: a species whose impact on community structure is disproportionately large relative to its biomass or abundance. Option B is incorrect because it misidentifies the cascade direction. A bottom-up cascade originates at the producer level — for example, an increase in nutrients boosting phytoplankton, which then increases zooplankton, then fish. The sea otter scenario flows from top predator downward, making it top-down, not bottom-up. Option C is incorrect because sea otters do not regulate the ecosystem through competitive exclusion. They are predators, not competitors of sea urchins or kelp. Competitive exclusion refers to two species competing for the same resource, which does not describe the otter-urchin-kelp relationship. Option D is incorrect because apex predator and keystone species are NOT mutually exclusive categories — a species can be both simultaneously. Sea otters are frequently cited in AP Environmental Science as an example of a species that occupies a top trophic position AND qualifies as a keystone species. The keystone designation is based solely on whether a species has a disproportionately large effect on community structure relative to its biomass, regardless of trophic position or whether effects are direct or indirect."
