    "explanation": "Choice A is correct. In MacArthur-Wilson island biogeography theory, two key variables determine equilibrium species richness: immigration rate and extinction rate. Because both islands are the same distance from the mainland, immigration rates are equal for both islands. However, Island X is larger, which means it can support larger population sizes for each species. Larger populations are less vulnerable to random extinction events (demographic stochasticity), so the extinction rate is lower on Island X. This lower extinction rate shifts the equilibrium intersection point to a higher species richness, meaning Island X will support more species at equilibrium. Choice B is incorrect; island size does not affect how easily colonizing species locate an island — that is determined by distance from the mainland. Choice C is incorrect because while equal distance does mean equal immigration rates, immigration rate is only one of the two variables. The islands differ in size, which affects extinction rates, so equilibrium species richness will not be equal. Choice D is incorrect because the scenario states both islands are the same distance from the mainland, and distance — not size — is the variable that affects immigration rate in MacArthur-Wilson theory."
