    "explanation": "Choice A is correct. In MacArthur-Wilson theory, the equilibrium number of species is determined by the intersection of the immigration rate curve and the extinction rate curve. Because both islands are the same size, their extinction rate curves are essentially the same. However, Island A's proximity to the mainland produces a higher immigration rate curve, shifting the equilibrium intersection point to a higher species richness. It is also worth noting that proximity can marginally reduce extinction via the 'rescue effect,' in which struggling populations are more easily recolonized from the mainland — this further favors higher richness on Island A, reinforcing the prediction. The dominant and determining factor, however, remains the higher immigration rate. Choice B is incorrect because MacArthur-Wilson theory does not predict that species surviving longer dispersal distances are better adapted or have lower extinction rates; extinction rates in the model are primarily driven by island size and population dynamics on the island, not by the traits selected during dispersal. Choice C is incorrect because while island size does set the extinction rate curve, distance independently sets the immigration rate curve; both curves together determine the equilibrium, so distance absolutely affects equilibrium richness even when size is held constant. Choice D is incorrect because endemic speciation as a compensatory mechanism for low immigration is not a prediction of MacArthur-Wilson equilibrium theory, and the claim that this process would produce convergence within 500 years is implausible on ecological timescales — speciation operates over much longer evolutionary timescales and is outside the scope of the MacArthur-Wilson model."
