    "format": "text",
    "question": "A population of deer in a forest reserve is monitored over one year. Biologists record 40 births, 15 deaths, 5 individuals immigrating into the reserve, and 10 individuals emigrating out. What is the net change in population size for that year?",
    "choices": [
      "A) +20",
      "B) +25",
      "C) +30",
      "D) +35"
    ],
    "answer": 0,
    "explanation": "The correct answer is A) +20. Net population change = Births - Deaths + Immigration - Emigration = 40 - 15 + 5 - 10 = +20. Choice B) +25 is incorrect; a common error is forgetting to subtract emigration, calculating only Births - Deaths + Immigration = 40 - 15 + 5 = 30, or alternatively subtracting only deaths and emigration from births without adding immigration: 40 - 15 = 25, ignoring both immigration and emigration equally but arriving at 25 by omitting immigration entirely from the correct formula. Choice C) +30 is incorrect; this results from a student who subtracts only emigration from births while ignoring deaths entirely: 40 - 10 = 30, a misconception that overlooks mortality as a factor reducing population. Choice D) +35 is incorrect; this results from a student who adds births and immigration and then subtracts only emigration, ignoring deaths entirely: 40 + 5 - 10 = 35, a misconception that overlooks the role of mortality in population dynamics."
