    "explanation": "The correct answer is A. Ocean-ocean convergent boundaries are defined by the subduction of one oceanic plate beneath another. This process creates a deep ocean trench at the subduction zone, generates magma as the subducting slab releases water into the mantle (lowering its melting point), and produces a chain of volcanic islands called an island arc parallel to the trench. Option B is incorrect because divergent boundaries are where plates move apart, forming mid-ocean ridges and rift valleys, not trenches or island arcs; additionally, 'ocean-continent divergent' is not a standard boundary classification. Option C is incorrect because transform boundaries involve plates sliding horizontally past each other, producing earthquakes but no volcanism or trenches. Option D is incorrect because continental-continental convergent boundaries produce mountain ranges like the Himalayas rather than ocean trenches or island arcs, since neither plate subducts easily due to low density."
